UML:TaggedValue.value: The Calendar App is a smart phone application, which offers the consignee convenient time slots for picking up goods, by sharing the calendar data with the transporter.

The Eco-Drive map-matcher component is responsible for map-matching positions received by vehicles in the fuel consumption report.
Service Interface: IMapMatcher
Service Operations:
RoadSegment matchPosition(position, lastPosition, drivenDistance)

The Eco-drive web HMI serves the web-based user interface to the users web browser. It lets the end user view and compare the eco-drive performance of different drivers. The Eco-Drive Web HMI uses the IEcoDriveStats-interface of the Eco-Drive Statistics Module.

The Eco-Drive Persistence component is responsible for the information store in the Eco-Drive portal. It exposes a service interface, IEcoDrivePersistence which exposes operations for inserting, updating and retrieving eco-drive data.
Service Interface: Eco-Drive Persistence Service Operations: storeFuelConsData(roadSegment, consumedFuel, vehicleWeight) Stores fuel consumption data in the database fetchFuelConsData(roadSegment, vehicleWeight) Fetch fuel consumption data from the database

The Eco-Drive Statistics Module provides an API for other components to retrieve fuel consumption statistics for different drivers on different road segments, also taking into different vehicle characteristics.
Service Interface: IEcoDriveStats Operations: List<FuelConsData> getFuelCons(List<RoadSegment> segments, VehicleType type, WeightClass class) Retrieves fuel consumption for all vehicles of given type and weight class.

The Eco-Drive Vehicle component implements the IEcoDriveVehicle interface, which lets vehicles and drivers connected to the service upload and exchange fuel consumption data with other vehicles and drivers.
Service Interface: IEcoDriveVehicle Service Operations subscribeFuelConsData(subscriber) Subscribes to fuel consumption statistics for distances driven by the vehicle. unsubscribeFuelConsData(subscriber) Unsubscribes to fuel consumption statistics. sendFuelConsData(position, drivenDistance, consumedFuel, weight) Upload fuel consumption data
The mobile router is the component managing communication to external entities, such as 3G/LTE and 802.11p.
The Message Manager is a component responsible for generating formatting and receiving messages over 802.11p, such as the traffic light signal phase information in UC2D.01.

The vehicle sensordata API provides access to sensor data on the in-vehicle network.
Service Interface: ISenorDataRead
readSignal(String name, byte[] output) Read data from a signal
subscribeSignal(String name, SignalSubscriber subscriber) Subscribe to signal changes
unsubscribeSignal(SignalSubscriber subscriber) Unsubscribe to signal changes
Service Interface: ISensorDataWrite
writeSignal(String name, byte[] value) Write signal data. For security reasons this is generally not possible.

The Local Dynamic Map is a data-store within an ITS-station (such as a vehicle or a road side unit), which support ITS-applications by maintaining information about objects influencing or being part of traffic. The data stored in the LDM is received from different sources such as vehicles, infrastructure units, traffic centres and on-board sensors.
Type 1: permanent static data, usually provided by a map data supplier. Type 2: transient static data, obtained during operation, e.g. changed static speed limits. Type 3: transient dynamic data, e.g. weather situation, traffic information. Type 4: highly dynamic data, e.g. cooperative awareness messages.
The LDM is not foreseen to contain type 1 data, since it is currently not considered feasible to define one common map data and specify an interface to that data, which meets the requirements for all ITS-stations. In cases where LDM data is of relevance to applications which uses type 1 data, location referencing of the LDM data is performed to relate it with the map data. Location referencing is a rather complex operation and since not all ITS applications using and LDM require location referenced information, the use of location referencing is not mandatory in the standard. Two standardised methods for location referencing are OpenLR (which is an industry standard) and Agora-C (which is an ISO standard).
The InstantMobility-project will not define its own LDM, as the LDM is currently being standardized by ETSI. A short description of the interfaces of relevant to the InstantMobility use cases will follow.
Service Interface: ILDMDataAccess
Service Operations:
subscribeSignalPhase(SignalPhaseSubscriber)
Subscribe to traffic light signal phase information of relevance for the vehicle.
unsubscribeSignalPhase(SignalPhaseSubscriber)
Unsubscribe to traffice light signal phase information.
Service Interface: ILDMDataProcessing
Service Operations:
processSignalPhaseData(SignalPhaseDataMsg msg)
Inserts or updates the signal phase information from a traffic light.

The Haptic Pedal Control component is an in-vehicle component responsible setting the haptic accelerator pedal resistence based on the current traffic situation fetched from the local dynamic map, such as traffic lights about to turn red or braking vehicles in-front.

The eco-drive advice generator is an in-vehicle module responsible for generating eco-drive advice from vehicle sensor data.
Service Interface: ISubscribeEcoDriveAdvice
Service Operations:
subscribeEcoDriveAdvice(subscriber)
Subscribe to eco driver advice.
unsubscribeEcoDriveAdvice(subscriber)
Unsubscribe from eco drive advice.

The Eco-Drive HMI is an in-vehicle component responsible for displaying eco-drive advice to the driver. The eco-drive advice is generated both from vehicle sensor data and from fuel consumption statistics data from the eco-drive portal.

The Eco-Drive Data Portal Exchanger is an in-vehicle module responsible for exchanging fuel consumption data with the Eco-Drive Portal. It provides a service interface, ISubscribeEcoDriveComparsion, which lets clients subscribe/unsubscribe from fuel consumption data generated by the portal.
Service Interface: ISubscribeEcoDriveComparsion
Service Operations:
subscribeFuelConsData(subscriber)
Subscribes to fuel consumption data
unsubscribeFuelConsData(subscriber)
Unsubscribes from fuel consumption data

The SmartGoodsGateway acts as an IPv6 router which connects the intelligent goods items to the transport management system. The SmartGoodsGateway receives router solicitation requests from the intelligent goods items over IEEE802.15.4. The router solicitation is answered by a router advertisement, providing the intelligent goods item with connection configuration.
6LowPAN brings IP and IPv6 to wireless sensor networks using 802.15.4.

Compared to a typical Internet node, smart objects are characterized by small memory and low processing power, which means that traditional operating systems need much more resources than what a smart object has. Typical microcontrollers for smart objects have RAM and ROM memory in the order of a few kilobytes each, which is a factor one million less than a personal computer. However, there exist operating systems for these devices as well. Contiki, TinyOS and FreeRTOS are three open source alternatives.

The smart goods service is a software component which executes on the microcontroller of an intelligent goods item.
Service Interface: IIdentification
String getGoodsId() Get an unique identifier of the goods item.
Service Interface: ISensorData
double getHighestG(Timestamp &timestamp) Get the highest recorded G force value recorded over the trip
double getHighestTemp(Timestamp &timestamp) Get the highest recorded temperature.
double getLowestTemp(Timestamp &timestamp) Get the lowest recorded temperature.
The Transport Booker API provides an interface to which the transport booker can post transport booking documents.

The Itinerary Processor create transport itineraries based on the transport bookings and the transport requests in the system.
Service Interface: INotifyChange
Service Operations:
transportBookingChanged(long bookingId) Notifies the itinerary processor that a transport booking was changed (added, updated or deleted)
transportResourceChanged(long resourceId) Notifies the itinerary processor that a transport resource was changed (added, updated or deleted)
Service Interface: IProposalMgmt
Service Operations:
updatePropositions(consigneeId, Calendar cal) Update or create new itinerary propositions based on calendar data.
List<Itinerary> getItineraryPropositions(long fleetId) Get all itinerary propositions that belongs to transport resources of a given fleet.
proposeItinerary(long itineraryId, long consigneeId) Send pick-up timeslot propositions to a consignee for acceptance
acceptItinerary(long itineraryId) Accept a proposed itinerary

The Transport Booking Persistence module is responsible for creating, retrieving, updating and deleting transport bookings from the datastore.
Service Interface: ITransportBookingPersistence
Service Operations:
addTransportBooking(TransportBooking booking) Adds a new transport booking
updateTransportBooking(TransportBooking booking) Updates an existing transport booking
deleteTransportBooking(long transportBookingId) Deletes an existing transport booking
List<TransportBooking> getTransportBookingsForConsignee(long consigneeId) Finds transport bookings by consignee
List<TransportBooking> getNonAssignedTransportBookings() Finds all non-assigned transport bookings

The Itinerary Persistence module is responsible for creating, retrieving, updating and deleting transport itineraries from the database.
Service Interface: IItineraryPersistence
Service Operations:
addItinerary(Itinerary itinerary) Adds a new itinerary
updateItinerary(Itinerary itinerary) Updates an existing itinerary
deleteItinerary(long itineraryId) Deletes an existing itinerary
List<Itinerary> getItinerariesForPeriod(Date startDate, Date endDate) Finds itineraries for a time period

The Transport Resource Persistence module is responsible for creating, retrieving, updating and deleting transport resources from the datastore.
Service Interface: ITransportResourcePersistence
Service Operations:
addTransportResource(transportResource)
Adds a transport resource to the system
updateTransportResource(transportResource)
Update an existing transport resource
deleteTransportResource(transportResourceId)
Delete an existing transport resource
List<TransportResource> getTransportResources()
Get all transport resources registered in the system

The Transport Booking Manager receives transport booking requests from the Transport Booking API and is responsible for registering these into the system.
Service Interface: ITransportBookingMgmt
Service Operations:
createTransportBooking(TransportBooking booking) Create a new transport booking.
updateTransportBooking(TransportBooking booking) Update an existing transport booking.
deleteTransportBooking(long transportBookingId) Remove an existing transport booking.

Input: Requests for creating, updating, retrieving and deleting transport resources. Output: Transport resource storage requests The Transport Resource Manager receives requests for creating, updating, retrieving and deleting transport resources.

The Transport Resource Mgmt HMI is a web user interface used by the transport planner in order to both add/modify/delete transport resources and manage the allocation of these, such as accepting/denying itinerary propositions.
Input: User actions for updating, retrieving and deleting transport resources. Output: Requests to the Transport Resource Manager module for creating, updating, retrieving and deleting transport resources.

The typical client of the Consignee API is a smartphone application used by the consignee in order to share calendar data and receive goods pick-up proposals. The Consignee API implements the FI-WARE DATA/Publish-Subscribe context broker, in order to be able to notify its client of new pick-up time propositions.
Service Interface: IItineraryAcceptance Service Operation: bool acceptItinerary(itineraryId) Accepts a given itinerary proposition, returns true if the acceptance was successful (i.e. done in a timely manner).
Service Interface: ICalendarUpdate This interface uses the CalWS-REST protocol for sharing calendar information, as defined by the CalConnect consortium.
